For example: The Pareto distribution has a pdf which is defined for formula_18 (the minimum value, formula_19 being the scale parameter) and its support, therefore, has a lower limit of formula_20 Since the support of formula_21 is dependent on the value of the parameter, the family of Pareto distributions does not form an exponential family of distributions (at least when formula_22 is unknown).

Another example: Bernoulli-type distributions – binomial, negative binomial, geometric distribution, and similar – can only be included in the exponential class if the number of Bernoulli trials, formula_23 is treated as a fixed constant – excluded from the free parameter(s) formula_1 – since the allowed number of trials sets the limits for the number of &quot;successes&quot; or &quot;failures&quot; that can be observed in a set of trials.

