:* The Iverson bracket is a generalization of the discrete delta-function: If the bracketed expression is true, the bracket has value 1; if the enclosed statement is false, the Iverson bracket is zero. There are many variant notations, e.g. wavey brackets: is equivalent to the notation used above.

The three variants of the categorical distribution and multinomial distribution are due to the fact that the parameters formula_142 are constrained, such that

:formula_143

Thus, there are only formula_144 independent parameters.
*Variant 1 uses formula_145 natural parameters with a simple relation between the standard and natural parameters; however, only formula_144 of the natural parameters are independent, and the set of formula_145 natural parameters is nonidentifiable. The constraint on the usual parameters translates to a similar constraint on the natural parameters.
*Variant 2 demonstrates the fact that the entire set of natural parameters is nonidentifiable: Adding any constant value to the natural parameters has no effect on the resulting distribution. However, by using the constraint on the natural parameters, the formula for the normal parameters in terms of the natural parameters can be written in a way that is independent on the constant that is added.
*Variant 3 shows how to make the parameters identifiable in a convenient way by setting formula_148 This effectively &quot;pivots&quot; around formula_149 and causes the last natural parameter to have the constant value of 0. All the remaining formulas are written in a way that does not access formula_150, so that effectively the model has only formula_144 parameters, both of the usual and natural kind.
Variants 1 and 2 are not actually standard exponential families at all. Rather they are &quot;curved exponential families&quot;, i.e. there are formula_144 independent parameters embedded in a formula_145-dimensional parameter space. Many of the standard results for exponential families do not apply to curved exponential families. An example is the log-partition function formula_154, which has the value of 0 in the curved cases. In standard exponential families, the derivatives of this function correspond to the moments (more technically, the cumulants) of the sufficient statistics, e.g. the mean and variance. However, a value of 0 suggests that the mean and variance of all the sufficient statistics are uniformly 0, whereas in fact the mean of the formula_155th sufficient statistic should be formula_156. (This does emerge correctly when using the form of formula_154 shown in variant 3.)

== Moments and cumulants of the sufficient statistic ==

